    public interface IMessage
    A message needs to support the following properties:
    • Each message must have a unique identifier.
    • Each message must be able to support any number of error listeners. These can be notified if the processing of a message fails at any point.
    • Each message may optionally carry history information with it.
    Error listeners are useful when a message can be processed by a chain of independent processes which do not know of each others existence. Despite not knowing of each other, they may well be interested if downstream processing of a message fails. If this is the case for a given processor, it can register itself with the message as an error listener. If a message processing component encounters an error processing a message, it should notify all error listeners registered with that message.

      • getRoutingHint

        Object getRoutingHint()
        Returns hint on where the message is destined to be sent.

        May be null.

        This may be useful to distinguish the direction of messages. For example, in a point to point connection between a stock broker and a stock market, this hint may return one of two possible values which indicate whether the message is heading to the market or to the broker. This sort of distinction would be useful in components that process messages in both directions. The component would receive the message and then may process it differently depending on the direction the message is heading.

        Returns:
        An object indicating the ultimate destination of the message. May be null.
